<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="10" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[174,1127,732,1127]" pageId="1" pageNumber="10">
The genus contained two species until now, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Walker, 1872)" baseAuthorityName="Walker" baseAuthorityYear="1872" box="[777,1073,732,758]" class="Insecta" family="Rhyparochromidae" genus="Aristaenetus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="diffinis">
<emphasis box="[777,890,732,758]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="10">A. diffinis</emphasis>
(Walker, 1872)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Woodward et O'Donnell, 1988" authorityName="Woodward et O'Donnell" authorityYear="1988" box="[174,673,765,792]" class="Insecta" family="Rhyparochromidae" genus="Aristaenetus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="similis">
<emphasis box="[174,284,765,792]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="10">A. similis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="WOODWARD, T. E. &amp; O'DONNELL, J. E." box="[292,673,765,792]" pageId="1" pageNumber="10" pagination="481 - 491" refId="ref5156" refString="WOODWARD, T. E. &amp; O'DONNELL, J. E. (1988): The genus Aristaenetus Distant (Hemiptera: Lygaeidae: Rhyparochrominae) with the description of a new species. - Memoirs of the Queensland Museum 25 (2): 481 - 491." type="journal article" year="1988">Woodward et O'Donnell, 1988</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, both known from 
<collectingCountry box="[912,1028,765,791]" name="Australia" pageId="1" pageNumber="10">Australia</collectingCountry>
. WOODWARD and O'DONNELL (1988) redescribed the genus in detail, therefore we will not repeat it, some additions and changes follow here.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="10" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[174,1127,732,1127]" pageId="1" pageNumber="10">Midline of head with micropunctures or transverse wrinkles. Clypeus convex in lateral view, always transversely rugose. Eyes without visible setae. Head diverging anteriad of eyes to antennal junction.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[174,1127,732,1127]" pageId="1" pageNumber="10">Anterior lobe of pronotum with sparse punctures, finer than on posterior lobe, anterolateral trichobothria sometimes absent. Sternum with impunctate, sparsely and densely punctate areas as well. Evaporative area extending on mesopleuron, forming a triangle, and as narrow line, extended to dorsal margin of metapleuron.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
